I  arrived early for a doctor's appointment at the Harvard Pilgrim health care center about two or three blocks away and decided to stop here for breakfast.   I ordered the Eggs Benedict.  I ordered the eggs "very soft" and they were perfect. But Instead of hollandaise the sauce was a cheese sauce.   Not what I expected.  Whenever I think about reviews I'm reminded of an equation I heard about a long time ago.   Happiness  = Reality - Expectations.  I was less than happy but the service was excellent and the breakfast was otherwise very good.

Excellent customer service and delicious food! From the moment we walked in, we were given great customer service.  The woman who greeted and seated us was friendly, the woman who served us was knowledgeable and gave us a tour of the menu and the chef actually came out of the kitchen to check in and see how the food and our experience was.  The Salmon Benedict was well done and came with 3 eggs which was a pleasant surprise. The homemade hash brown was unique and tasty.  We also ordered the cherry banana french toast special which was a great blend of sweet fruit that complimented the thick french toast -- no syrup was needed with that dish.

Good: prices very fair, they don't pre-butter everything, small staff but pretty good service.  Mixed: Unlike some in the area, they don't automatically pile home-fries on every breakfast plate. (Not sure they offer home fries, actually.) Good if you're trying to cut down on calories, but it does account for part of the price difference.  Disappointed by: the pancake batter. Try the French toast next time.  Overall: there is likely to be a next time.

I have to say the owner / operator is very personal and hands on. The food its self is very bland!  Under seasoned eggs. Its like they use non stick pans with no butter no oil no salt no pepper. the food looks good to the eye by taste nothing like it will look like. Hash over cooked. Prob frozen heat and serve. The French toast  is dry. How do you do that? I mean its soak in a milk cinnamon and egg mixture and toasted on a griddle but the toast is dry ..... How Sway.  I call in because there are limited options to choose from for breakfast in Medford. By limited i mean none.  Reading all these great reviews, I'm wondering if the owner has change  kitchen staff or menu. I've had better breakfast at my kids elementary school.  People want to start their day off right. Not here... Nope .... This is the type of breakfast your wife makes you when she asking for a divorce and tells you your oldest son is not your but your best friends.  I suggest Light House staff visits the restaurants below as a secret shop and see if they are truly on par for hometown cooking.  1) Reds Salem ( Breakfast) 2) Reds Danvers (lunch and dinner options) 3) Brothers Deli Lynn and Wakefield (Breakfast and lunch)

Owners - you should be ashamed of yourselves for allowing items of that poor quality to be delivered to paying customers.

Amazingly good food. We went here on our last day in Boston. We found the restaurant in a list of must visit restaurants in the Medford area. We decided to go and check it out for breakfast. Upon arrival the employees seemed very cheerful and directed us to a nice table. I had the pancakes and I have to say they were the best pancakes EVER!!! The hash browns and bacon come in good sized portions also. I would recomend this to anyone that likes amazing and affordable food for the whole family.

The omelets are made with =5= eggs, with the normal choices plus some off the beaten path, like mushrooms with boursin cheese. The banana French toast is fantastic. The fruit bowls are incredible in quantity and quality. Coffee refills are definitely not just a theoretical concept here. Very, very reasonable prices for what's delivered. I almost get the impression that Justin Sargent's verbatim-double posts belonged to a different place, because I've never seen a waiter there, the waitresses I've seen are never in "basically pajamas," and I've never had a dirty glass.
